	Bhupathi, Knowles lose final  New Haven (US): Mahesh Bhupathi rsquo;s quest for a second successive ATP Pilot Pen doubles title ended in dejection on Sunday after the Indian ace and his Bahamian partner Mark Knowles went down in straight sets against Brazilians Marcelo Melo and Andre Sa.  The second-seeded Indo-Bahamian lost the final match 5-7, 2-6 to their fourth seeded rivals in one hour and 22-minutes. Bhupathi and Knowles double faulted seven times and were broken four times and could convert just one of the four break points.
      
	Trescothick admission  London: Former England cricketer Marcus Trescothick has reportedly admitted using sweets to alter the ball rsquo;s swing during the 2005 Ashes series.  The opener said the mints generated saliva which he then rubbed on the ball, according to excerpts from his autobiography, ldquo;Coming Back To Me, rdquo; serialised in Sunday rsquo;s edition of the News of the World newspaper.    
	 Gill thanks BCCI  New Delhi: Sports minister M.S. Gill on Sunday expressed gratitude towards the Board of Control for Cricket in India (BCCI) for its decision to give an annual grant of Rs 50 crore to National Sports Development Fund.  ldquo;BCCI is our richest sports institution and its president Sharad Pawar was kind enough to give Rs 25 crore for the development of other games to the National Sports Development Fund. But I wanted them to raise the help to Rs 50 crore a year and I am happy that Pawar and BCCI have decided to give Rs 50 crore a year, rdquo; Gill said.    
	 Ghei, Lahiri tied 49th  Bandar Seri Begawan (Brunei): Gaurav Ghei and Anirbhan Lahiri turned in their worst card of the week mdash; four-over 75s mdash; to sign off tied 49th at the Brunei Open on Sunday. The duo ended their campaign with a total of even-par 284. The other Indian in fray, Rahil Gangjee, finished tied 58th with a modest one-under 71.    
	 Table tennis  Calcutta: The All Bengal Bhowanipur Bayam Sangha Table Tennis Championship concluded on Sunday with an outstanding performance from Riya Dutta , says A Staff Reporter. Riya won in four categories (cadet girls, both the sub-junior girls and women).    
	ITF referee  Calcutta: The All India Tennis Association has nominated Joy Mukherjee as the tournament referee for the ITF Junior event and the Asian Series under-14 Championships to be held at Chennai and Bangalore in the second and third weeks of next month, says A Staff Reporter.
                                                                                                                                                               
